Part 2


"Fire lives the death of earth, and air lives the death of fire; water lives the death of air, earth that of water.'' -- Heraclitis

Valdayana took the notes and scanned through them briefly. 

"They appear to be the schematics for a series of seige machines and a tactical outline for an invasion." She handed them back to the ranger, who finally decided to sit down.

"Why would the gods go to such lengths?"

"If memory serves, the House of Zek never need provocation. Warfare alone is reason enough." 

"Remember when you first mentioned Zebuxoruk to me?" Millikin absently began to tap her fingers on the arm of her chair. Valdayana silently watched the ranger's twitching as she vaguely recalled the conversation. Millikin was never good at concealing her anxiety, though it rarely manifested as bouts of anger any longer. Nonetheless, the enchanter was still tempted on occasion to test how well the ranger had learned to refocus that energy.

"Yes." The Teir` Dal nodded after a moment's deliberation.

"He is currently imprisoned by the panthenon. The sage in the cells of Justice was right."

"That is not my concern." Valdayana shrugged.

"But it doesn't make sense. Why imprison him instead of killing him outright if he's a threat."

"For the same reason Kerafyrm was not." Valdayana answered. "They aren't powerful enough."

"Surely he had help though. Just like I was given the ability to travel to the outer realms."

"True to an extent. You were tested and found fit to be granted that power."

"Why?" 

"Without knowing the extent of what you were given, I can't venture to say for certain. But in all probability it is another test of sorts. Or a trap."

"What do you mean a trap?" Millikin's eyes narrowed at the implication.

"Consider what you learned, Ranger. The gods of Norrath seek the destruction of mortals. Or at the very least, ensure mortals remain under their control." 

"Some of them." Millikin nodded.

"If they can't obtain that by overt brute force they will resort to subversion." Valdayana continued. "They could be testing to see if anyone they can control may be powerful enough to eliminate any threats to their supremacy. Or simply giving those who may challenge their divinity just enough assistance to get into a situation that inevitably results in their destruction." 

"Like letting a child play with a sword." 

"An apt analogy." Valdayana remarked. 

"I saw them die... They died and imbued me with a portion of their essence."

"Who?" Valdayana asked.

"The elder gods. Xegony, the Rathe Council, Fennin Ro, and the Coirnav of the Triumvirate of Water." Millikin whispered.

"What are you talking about?' Valdayana peered at the ranger. With the substance of her ages-long search finally within her means and likely in the possession of the Feir` Dal standing before her, Valdayana D`Varr was remarkably self-possessed.

"I encountered the elemental gods in their home planes. When they died, they imbued a part of themself within me as well as leaving a remnant behind. At times I felt it pulling at me. Shifting, I don't know really. I can't explain it. You used this to find specific memories." Millikin held up the memory crystal. "Could you do something similiar to find out what it is they put within me. And possibly remove it."

"Do you realize what you're asking me to do, Ranger?" To be sure, the irony was not lost on Valdayana D` Varr.

"I'm asking for your help to extricate myself from the control of beings who would just as soon see us all exterminated. I have seen no intercession on our behalf by the gods supposedly concerned for our welfare." Millikin answered solemnly. 

"Do you have the fragments left behind by the gods?" 

"Yes." Millikin nodded.

"Then I will see what I can do."

