At that moment, Valdayana distanced herself from the mental link with the ranger.  There was always a danger in losing one's own sense of self when experiencing another's memories, and even moreso due to the fact that the ranger's memories of the incident had not faded with the passage of time.  The enchanter decided to shift her concentration on the link to take the role of third party observer.  She watched the events unfold once more in the ranger's mind.  


Vegarlson, the Earthen Badlands  (The Plane of Earth)

To say that mortals were unwelcome in the elemental planes would be a vast understatement.  Valdayana watched as the ranger was attacked by denizens of the plane.  In a series of rituals demonstrating strength and endurance, the ranger and her companions drew the attention of the Mystical Arbitor of Earth who summoned them beneath the caves past the gigantic basilisk that stood as the sentinel to crystal caves that led to the Rathe Council's sanctum.  The earth elemental was created to arbitrate demands by the lesser gods and their demi-divine subordinates seeking audience with the Rathe Council.  It was somewhat suprised to see a group of mortals petitioning entry into Ragrax.  This was unheard of.  Mortals were not to be permitted access to the elemental planes and were to be summarily destroyed if they were found.  Invariably, the arbitor found itself crumbling into pebbles before the onslaught.  Its essense dispersed itself upon the assemblage, allowing them to pass through the mystical barriers that protected the Rathe Council's fortress.


Ragrax, the Stronghold of the Twelve, (The Plane of Earth)

Ragrax was a fortress manned by golems constructed of dirt and mud, vekerchiki, slightly more powerful versions of an earth mephit, and moss covered humanoids possessing shamantic powers.  The defense was overseen by a contingent of stone giants led by an elder giant warlord named Gintolakan.  It was a simple matter of bypassing or destroying the golems, mephits, and humanoids.  The giants were another matter.  Their defensive outline required intruders to conquer the fortress in sections.  Three watchposts formed a mystical barrier manned by several giants and commanded by a chieftain.  One pylon must be seized by potential invaders before moving to the next one.  Usually by the time the third pylon is taken, Warlord Gintolakan is alerted and arrives to challenge any who dare to attempt to breech the Rathe's inner sanctum.  Warlord Gintolakan had been blessed by the Rathe with the ability to command pebbles and dust to slow opponents as well as summon a comet to strike at his foes with bone shattering force.  But for all his formidable strength, it did not take the ranger and her companions long to realize that he was easily distracted.  Perhaps he could not see well, between the perpetual dust and comparative differences in size, or perhaps he was just slow witted.  In any event the giant was eventually slain, the key granting him access to the Rathe's inner sanctum was claimed.

The Rathe were assembled in a grove of petrified trees surrounded by a river of muddy water.  Each looked identical to the other.  A giant piece of wood with features were carved with a knife.  Their only adornments were a toga made of moss and grass and each one carried a large gnarled staff.  The ranger cautiously approached the council who were seemingly oblivious to her presence then suddenly all of them turned to face her.

"You trespass here."  They spoke in unison.

"I seek your counsel."  Millikin responded.

"Transient mortal issues do not concern us." 

"You are the ones who are to help me complete the Quintessence of the Elements."  

"Why would we do this?"

"That's what I want to know."  The ranger replied.  "What is it for?"

"It gives the bearer access to time."  The Rathe Council answered.  "But you suspect this already.  Some mortals seek to disrupt the balance of power between mortality and divinity. You will act to prevent this.  Our avatar will give you what you require."

One by one the Rathe fell to the ground, their life's blood mingled with the dirt and stone of their homeland.  The ground shook and in the center of the grove, a single entity emerged from the ground, a singular councilman rose up, much taller than the predecessors.  The Rathe's avatar began to chant as it reached down to scoop up a handful of dirt at its feet.  Primal energy surged in its hand as it closed around the earth, turning it black.  Then the avatar opened its hand and dropped the sphere onto the ground at Millikin's feet.

