Part 9

You Can't Go Home Again

"When did you get taller, Dahlia?"  Millikin looked at the silver haired girl who was nearly eye level to her.

"While you were off wandering around.  You seem different too."  She beamed at the ranger before hugging her.  "Your last letter said you went to that new continent the bards are talking about."

Millikin returned the hug and nodded.  Taelosia, it is not a pleasant place.

"It can't be worse than Terris' realm can it?  And you never finished telling me what happened after the Plane of Water."  

"I didn't?"  Millikin got a vague expression on her face at the reference.

"No.  You didn't."

"Check again."  Millikin replied.  

"I keep everything you send me and it's not there."  Dahlia rolled her eyes.  "Does it have something to do with that dark elf you associate with.  What happened?"  

"It's a rather long story."

"We have time.  Mother and Father went to Felwithe for the day." 

"Since nothing else will please you."

Millikin recounted the events to her sister as they walked along the treetop platforms of Kelethin.  

"What did the quarm look like?"

"You've seen a picture of a hydra monster, yes?"

Dahlia nodded.

"Well... He had four dragon-like heads.  Each one a different color, red, green, black, and bluish white.  His body was a deep green color.  And he had long batlike wings.  But I don't think he could fly with them.  He's too big."

"How big was he?"

"He could easily look over the platforms while standing on the ground."

"Where did it come from?"  

"Mostly, the elemental gods summoned it to guard Zebuxoruk."  Millikin explained before going into detail about how they eventually slew it. 

"Pay your tribute here!  And perhaps the gods will turn their attention to us once more!"  

The statement immediately caught the ranger's attention.

"What's this?"

"That's one of the things that's changed recently."  Dahlia whispered.  "Mother says the elders say Tunare is silent."

"And who is this person?"  Millikin asked.

"Katryn Hidken.  A tribute master.  They can grant spells or something."  Dahlia explained.

"A what?!"  Millikin stormed up to the table where a handful of elves had gathered.

"What are you doing here?"  The ranger demanded of the woman who was taking money and items from a few younger elves who had gathered.

"You must have been away for awhile."  Katryn began.  "As some of the greedy people invaded the realms of our gods, the pantheon has decided to withdraw their blessings from mortals.  However, if proper penance and offerings are provided, Tunare will provide supplicants with...."

"Money.  So now the gods demand money from us as well?"  The ranger clenched her fists and tried to keep the anger out of her voice.

"Not necessarily money.  Other goods of value can be given as a sacrifice as well.  Do you wish to make a donation as well?  It's the only way to obtain Tunare's blessing."

Millikin grabbed an end of the collection table and hurled it to the side, scattering the containers of platinum, gold, and plethora of food, weapons, and armor the tribute master had obtained.  "She can keep her blessings then."  

"Mill..."  Dahlia whispered in horrified surprise.

"How dare you!"  Katryn glared daggers at the ranger.  "It's attitudes like yours that have caused the gods to withdraw their favor from us in the first place."

"My behavior.  You don't have any idea of what you're talking about."  Millikin gave the tribute master a look of utter contempt.

"Its no secret that bands of power mongering mercenaries have trampled through the gods' realm visiting destruction on their servants and plundering."

"Then of course you are also aware that while several gods of the panthenon were plotting the genocide of every race on Norrath, the rest of them decided to sit quietly back and not interfere in the slightest.  If it wasn't for the actions of those power mongering mercenaries, the entirety of Norrath would have been reduced to ash.  And you have the audacity to tell people they should pay the gods for their continued intercession?"

"You lie."  The tribute master sneered at Millikin.

"Do I?"  Millikin countered.  "Then why don't the gods strike me down for heresy?  You're wasting your time trying to gain the approval of a god who cares nothing about our fate.  You don't even have the slightest conception of what's waiting on the edge of this world because of their petty power plays."

"Be gone."  Katryn waved a dismissive hand at Millikin and bent down to pick up the scattered coins.

"Millikin..."  Dahlia tugged at the ranger's arm.  "Let's go."  The two walked off.

"And you say nothing interesting ever happens to you."  Dahlia grinned at Millikin.

Millikin told Dahlia everything that happened that evening.  The entire story of her battle with Quarm.  How her life force was torn from her body by the elder gods to complete their conjuration and left her where she fell.  Knowing they would be weakened in their collective attempt to imprison Zebuxoruk, they elemental powers stored part of their essence to recall it again later for a trap to kill any mortals who would question their decision.  Their plan was flawed in that they did not consider the machinations of a Teir` Dal enchanter's bid for divinity.  Valdayana D`Varr had seized the power they had placed in Millikin for her own and survived the apotheosis such an act would trigger.  

That night as the ranger fell into the elven reverie, she recalled the panthenon's reaction to Valdayana's ascension and grudging acceptance...

