Part 11

Exit

"Through dangers untold
And hardships unnumbered,
I have fought my way here
To the castle beyond the goblin city
For my will is as strong as yours
And my kingdom as great
You have no power over me."   -- A. C. H. Smith  (The Labyrinth)


Several months later, Millikin stood on the shores of Natimbi.  She had ventured into sites once venerated by the Nihilites, a race that had since fallen to corruption and the invasion forces of an entity known as Mata`Muram.  She learned of the tragic fate of the Trusik, cursed to exist for an eternity as apparitions re-enacting the last moments of their lives just prior to their deaths.  Many of them did not even realize they were ghosts that would re-materialize later even if put to the sword or destroyed by eldritch power.  Repeated expeditions became an exercise in futility and on more than one occasion the rationale for exploring through the ruined shrines was for plundering whatever valuables could be found, not finding a way to stop Mata`Muram's forces.  Nor did any of these excursions entail freeing the living Nihilites from Muramite oppression.  Millikin found the practice personally distasteful and since the skills of a ranger are not desired or needed by other individuals belonging to her formal association, she was often dismissed from participating.  She found herself with an inordinate amount of free time on her hands to wander on her own and contemplate matters.  It was just as well since she disliked the attitudes of the current powerbase that dictated policy.  Their presumptuous arrogance and boasts of success were nothing more than thinly veiled attempts at slaking their own greedy self-interests.  The Feir`Dal ranger dismissed it as typical human behavior but was growing weary of having any involvement in it, even if her role was only peripheral at best.

For her own part, Millikin Erreene had all but verbally forsworn any devotion she once held for Tunare.  She would not bring herself to defend the derogatory slurs often thrown around by the lesser races about the elves' patron deity.  The ranger scoffed at the idea of one being so callously indifferent to their creations as deserving of such an acknowledgement in the first place.  In fact she ceased using the magic she could once call upon in the goddess' name.  Not that anyone really noticed since the gods had long ago spurned granting their militant followers spells more effective than anything they granted their significantly less skilled and experienced members of the priesthood.  The handful of spells Millikin did use derived their power directly from the forces of the four elements or aspects of nature instead.  She extracted a fishing line and bait from her backpack and decided to pursue some fishing.

"Ranger."  

Millikin recognized the voice and glanced around but didn't see anyone even though her senses had developed to the point where she could see or smell most beings that could employ magics to hide themselves from normal vision.  She resumed watching her fishing line.

"Have you gone deaf, Ranger?"

"My hearing is fine."

"You did not acknowledge me."  

"You aren't present to acknowledge, Luhtmauyar D`Varr."

"Believe it or not I have other things to do that actually require my physical presence."  

"You're showing off and I'm not impressed."  Millikin watched in mild amusement as a crab snipped her fishing line and scurried to shore with bait and lure in tow.  Moments later, light began to shimmer around the crab as it began to transform into the dark elven enchanter.  She held out the fishing wire, lure, and worm to Millikin with obvious disdain.

"Here is your toy, Ranger."

"Don't you have better things to do besides antagonize me?"  Millikin took the line from the enchanter and began to untangle the lure from the fishing wire.

"And forget the little people who helped me get where I am today?"  Valdayana remarked loftily.

"How magnanimous of you."  Millikin rolled her eyes.

"A four syllable word.  Did someone teach the Feir`Dal ranger how to read a dictionary?"  The dark elf's tone was not quite acerbic.

"Yes, a condescending Teir`Dal enchanter who was old when trakaraptors roamed the Commonlands."  Millikin pointedly ignored Valdayana's incisive gaze as she worked to unravel the hook from her fishing line.

"You aren't traipsing through the Nihilite temples with your friends."  Valdayana commented absently.

"Do not insult the handful of people I consider my friends by presuming my association with a guild also makes them my friends.  They don't qualify and in fact many of them despise me.  But so long as I have some measurable worth to them they'll tolerate me.”  Millikin paused deliberately before continuing.   “They are like you in that regard.  Now what do you want?"

'What makes you think I want or need anything from you?"  Valdayana commented loftily.

"Because the only time anyone approaches me with the pretense of friendship or interest in me is when they want something." 

"Welcome to the real world, Ranger."  Valdayana remarked.  The neo-deity's remark only drew a slight glance from the ranger as she finished disentangling her fishing lure then put it away.  Moments later she pulled out a whittling knife and piece of wood from her pocket and resumed carving a piece of wood she was working with earlier.

"You are not happy."  Valdayana stated point-blank to the ranger.  "Granted you're more sullen than the rest of your flighty hedonistic kind, so it’s kind of hard to tell in most circumstances.  But I know you well enough to know when you are and when you're not."

"Are you so bored that now you've taken an interest in my personal well-being?”  Millikin remarked absently.

"I cannot have my followers unhappy."  Valdayana replied.

"I'm not your follower."  Millikin stated simply.  "Or anyone else's for that matter."

"Of course you are, Ranger.  You've followed my orders for years."

"If I did it was because I believed it was the right course of action.  Not because I feared you or expected any reward for it."

"This age is dying, Ranger."

"What was your first indication?  When all of a sudden people with absolutely no magical training or proclivities instantly developed magical powers literally overnight that made some of the most potent spells possessed by the most talented spellcasters worthless?  Or did the realization hit you recently that a spellcaster's power is no longer determined by their years of study, innate talent, and experience but solely the types of talismans they possess?  Honestly, it doesn't take any kind of intellectual giant to realize the natural order of existence is coming undone.  The gods themselves won't be unscathed before this is done."

"You think Mata`Muram is that powerful?  He couldn't even enter this reality without the help of mere mortals."  Valdayana replied.

"Mere mortals."  Millikin sighed.  "I've seen the geomantic magic the Nihilites are capable of wielding.  And while it's destructive aspect overshadows anything I've seen wielded by a Norrathian, their potential for creation and preservation outstrips their destructive capability by far.  Yet for all that power, the Trusik who tore into Mata`Muram's reality and freed him, are damned for eternity to an existence as ghosts reliving the final months of their destruction.  Only a fool would underestimate that."

"True enough."  Valdayana mused over the ranger's observations.  "What would you do about it?"

"There's nothing I can do."  Millikin began scraping the wood into a point.  "I served my purpose to Tunare.  And since I was discarded when my usefulness ended, I'll watch and wait until oblivion claims me."

"I want you to be my eyes and ears in other realms."

"I don't care what you want."  Millikin stated succinctly.

