Clearly that was not the response Valdayana D`Varr expected.  Her gaze narrowed slightly as she silently studied the ranger for several moments.

"Did you think because my patron deity abandoned me that I would eagerly become the adherent to the next one to solicit my worship?"

"Actually, yes."  Valdayana answered calmly.

"If I did then you'd still have been too late.  Priests of Discord never cease looking for followers."  The ranger remarked dryly as she turned the piece of wood over to begin whittling on the other side.

"What if I told you that this is part of a bigger picture beyond even Norrath and their pantheon."

"And I should care because..."  Millikin answered.  "The majority of my life was dedicated to helping others.  While I never expected any gratitude for it, I certainly didn't expect being treated like trash would be the norm either.  Nor will I tolerate being treated like such by degenerates anymore."

"Hence why I want you to work as my agent in other realities.  You have no place in Norrath anymore.  And the only time you are ever happy is when you are exploring.  I need to expand my influence.  To do that I need to know which worlds where I can do that most effectively."

"I'm not a proselytizer."  

"You are an efficient scout and pay attention to details.  You will represent my accumulation of esoteric knowledge.  So you needn't worry about the moral implications of anything."  Valdayana explained.

"And what worlds specifically are you talking about?"  Millikin inquired still not looking up from her carving.  "Presuming that I'm disposed to help you."

"Abeir-Toril.  Azeroth.  Eberron.  Thestra.  It's your choice."  

"I see.  And how am I to return if I want or need to?"

"You have the means already, if you recall.  Whenever you like."  Valdayana replied.

"Those are vague directions."  Millikin finished her carving.

"I will show you more specifically how to reach them if you accept my charge."  Valdayana answered.  "Privileged information and all."

"Very well.  I will accept your charge, Tura Valdayana D`Varr."  Millikin handed the carving to the former Teir`Dal who studied the icon for several moments.  It resembled a prowling fox.  She smiled sardonically.

"Keep it in remembrance of your commitment to me."  She handed it back to the ranger.
"One other thing.  Don't be surprised to find that your appearance may change from time to time.  It's a sometimes necessary side-effect for you to most effectively adapt to a given world."  The enchanter vanished almost as quickly as she had appeared

"Thanks for the warning."  Millikin took the fox carving back which was glowing faintly.  She slipped it into her pocket and left with the knowledge of how to reach her new destination.  

Later...

The ranger knew where the abandoned druidae rings were near Kelethin.  It took less than an hour to find the exact stone with the eroded sigils engraved on its side.  She had said her goodbyes to those who mattered a while ago.  As the eldritch light engulfed the wood elf ranger, she never looked back.

